===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
Uncertain.
The classical interpretation is an {{liushu|ic|nocap=1}}: a {{zh-l|*犬|dog}} guarding four {{zh-l|*口|vessels}}. 

It might also be a phonetically borrowed character, originally meaning “to [[bark#Verb|bark]]” (Compare {{zh-l|*狺}}).

Another theory states the character is derived from {{zh-l|*喪|mourning}}. (Compare {{zh-l|*噩}}, {{zh-l|*哭}} , {{zh-l|*咢}}). Borrowed not for sound but as an {{liushu|i|nocap=1}} referring to a funerary urn.

